Others again have thought that Rutilius’ position at Rome may have become untenable on account of the charges he brought against Stilich0, the general of Honorius, of having betrayed the Empire, of having allowed Alaric to enter Italy, and of having burned the Sibyllino Oracles. This theory, of course, cannot refer tozthe actual words used in II. 41 sq., as they were not written until Rutilius had already taken his departure; but no doubt he may have published the same charges in some other manner. The conjecture, however, in any case, cannot count ior much, as Stilicho had been put to death by the Emperor Honorius in 408, some eight years before Rutilius' departure from Rome, and charges that showed Stilicho in an invidious light would tend to justify Honorius in putting him to death, and so would strengthen and not weaken Rutilius’ standing in the Emperor's favour.
